element.name: 19 A Walk in the Garden-Lugnagun to Sorrel by Kili or bust, Multi-cache (2/3)
element.long-description:
Visit The Geocaching Ireland discussion forum HERE
High on my hills of dreams -
Dear hills that know me!
And then how fair will seem
The land below me!
How pure, at vesper-time
The far bells chiming!
God, give me hills to climb
And strength for climbing.
(A.Guiterman)
A walk in the garden county on low level hills with moderate hiking and some rough sections including fences. A round trip of two to two and a half hours should complete this one as much of the walking is on forest roads. There are boggy sections and one moderate ascent and it should be NOTED that there are some fences to be crossed (one or two have stiles and others don't). The total distance is nine and a half Kilometres with a total ascent of only 342 metres.
There is a megalithic tomb about half way between Lugnagun and Sorrel which you pass twice but I was unable to locate it during my treks.
To get to the summit of Lugnagun climb up along the edge of the wood on some rough ground, overlooking the area where the 1798 men and women had their camp. These rebels were under the command of the Dublin lawyer Colonel McMahon and they mainly came from Kildare, Dublin and Wicklow.
According to my map, (taken from East West Mapping) Wat Read, presumably a rebel leader, was hanged near the summit of Lugnagun but again I was unable to unearth any detailed information about him.
This camp was later joined by the experienced commander from Roundwood, (General) Joseph Holt. The camp was then moved from there to the more elevated and rugged Whelp Rock area near Black Hill.
The cache is placed a modest distance above Ballynultagh car park where you should finish.
***NOTE: It is perfectly possible to do this hiking cache AND its neighbouring one on Black Hill in the one trip using the same car park to start and finish.
You may require a pen and paper. To find this cache you will need to start a little distance down the road at N53 08.475 W006 27.655 and head for Stage 1 at N53 08.680 W006 28.178. There is a fork in the track shortly after the start. You should stay left at this. Reaching Stage 1 you will find a thick fence post and 2 numbers. Call these in ascending order AB.
Turn North uphill to Ref. 1 at N53 08.711 W006 28.150 where you will find a gate behind which is a black and yellow barrier. Climb over and head up the forest track to the right till you reach Ref 2 at N53 08.900 W006 28.701. Here the forest road splits but you can take either one to reach Stage 2. My advice is to take the left one as the distance is the same but the views along the lake are quite stunning in nice weather on that side. If you take this option you will need to keep right at Ref 3 at N53 08.887 W006 29.091.
To access Stage 2, as advised above, you will need to cross rough ground (leaving the forest track at N53 09.247 W006 29.656 where the forest has been cut and head toward the summit of Lugnagun following close to the fence along the wood. When I did this hike last there were a number of trees down but it was easy work to get around them. Stay in the forest until you reach Stage 2.
Stage 2 is at N53 09.298 W006 29.414.
Here you will find 2 more numbers (one post to the lake side of the corner post!. Call these, in ascending order CD.
From there exit the wood and then you will need to walk along the forest edge Eastward in the direction of Sorrel which you should be able to see in the distance and reaching Stage 3 along the way. This route is rough hiking with several fences some of which have stiles.
Look for the corner edge of the forest.
Stage 3 is at N53 08.814 W006 28.060
Here you will find 3 more numbers. Call these, in ascending order FGE as they appear.
Follow the bog path up the hill to Sorrel summit and find Stage 4
Stage 4 is at N53 08.871 W006 26.607
Find 3 more numbers here and call them, in ascending order HJI.
Final Cache: N53 AB.CDE W006 FG.HIJ
There is a narrow bog track down to the cache and the car park at Ballynultagh from the summit of Sorrel Hill. While at the cairn on top look SE about 50 metres away where there is a peat hag ridge with a small but clear gap. Follow this winding route down as it is by far the easiest way to the cache and the road.
From Mountain Views:
Lugnagun Hill Wicklow County
Height: 446 metres OS 1/50k Mapsheet: 56 for top Grid Ref: O01252 12476
Latitude: 53.153445 Longitude: -6.487263 ITM: 701179 712506
Lugnagun is the 633rd highest summit in Ireland.
Sorrel Hill Mountain Wicklow County
Height: 599 metres OS 1/50k Mapsheet: 56 for top
Grid Ref: O04201 11925 Latitude: 53.147928 Longitude: -6.443379 ITM: 704127 711956
Sorrel Hill is the 280th highest summit in Ireland.
Do not start the trek without all the proper mountain rain gear, waterproof boots and the guidance material, compass, map, GPSr with mapping etc. Please note that all parts of this cache are hiked at your own risk. The cache owner takes no responsibility of any sort for any reason including accidents or mishaps. THERE ARE SOME FENCES TO CROSS BUT NO NEED TO ENTER PRIVATE PROPERTY. JUST BE AWARE OF THE NECESSITY TO CROSS THEM SOMETIMES WITHOUT THE HELP OF STILES.
Please be aware that cars parked in areas close to walking trails are vulnerable and they can be vandalised or stolen. Unfortunately this is an ongoing problem which is extremely difficult to solve. so there is a risk involved.
Please observe the country code to the best of your ability. Local landowners often generously allow access to upland areas across or through parts of their private property. Please, please be conscious of this and return the courtesy by keeping all gates closed, immediately and not on your way back!. Please use the gates where appropriate but if you have to climb over them then use the hinged side ONLY.
Please do not cause any damage of any sort to fences or barriers along the way.
Piece from Mountain Views about Sorrel Hill.
"In Irish, I have seen this hill referred to as ‘Cor tSamhaidh’, the Round Hill of the Sorrel. The sorrel in question is obviously the plant of that name, called ‘samhadh’ in Irish (‘Rumex acetosa’ in botany). It is the long-leaved common sorrel that often ends up in our salads. One would therefore expect an abundance of the plant here, if it did give its name to the hill, yet I have so far never found a specimen. Then again, I have never gone out avidly looking for one, either. Leaving this botanical conundrum aside, the most notable feature on Sorrel is the megalithic cairn on its summit, which has a diameter of about 20m. (Enterprising modern hands have added a further small cairn to the original beneath.) Just to the left of the mound, can be seen in the distance the cluster of Seefin, Seefingan and Seahan, equally crowned with megaliths. These hills lie between 6 and 8kms away, across the valley of the Liffey. There are other remnants of the past in the immediate vicinity, too, though they are difficult to find. On the broad saddle between Sorrel and Lugnagun there are, reportedly, traces of several Stone Age enclosures (detectable in aerial photography) and another cairn about 10m in diameter, but I have looked for them in vain in this very broken terrain. A little further on, inside the forest fence, there is a small megalithic tomb (marked, this time, on the OSI map), but now so hemmed in by forest that it is in danger of being totally engulfed (Coillte protecting our heritage!). One thing our megalithic forebears did not see from the top of Sorrel is, of course, the 11 kilometre long Pollaphuca Reservoir to the west. Although we know today that there was, in fact, a lake there between 15,000 and 10,000 years ago, fed by meltwater from a glacier, it had long disappeared before the builders of the megaliths ever came upon the scene. The dam that forms the present lake, dating from 1940, has given us a view of the past that makes even Stone Age man a recent blow-in by comparison".
